        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The line width of C17O emission is expected to be ~10 km/s, for which we adopt a relatively large bandwidth of 0.86 km/s, indicating that the number of spectral resolution elements per line width is approximately 10. Since our aim is to make a spatially resolved C17O flux map, such a modest bandwidth is optimized to realize the spatial resolution and flux sensitivity high enough within realistic observation times. The other three spectral windows are devoted to continuum emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Referring to Qi et al. (2011, see also Figure 3 in this proposal), the angular size of the disk around HR 163296 as seen with C17O is about 5.0 arcsec. Hence, the proposed largest angular scale (7.0 arcsec) is essential to cover the whole of our target. The requested angular resolution (0.4 arcsec) is also necessary for making a detailed map of C17O. In particular, assuming a distance to the target to be 120 pc, the CO snow line (~150 AU) is located at the disk radius of 1.2 arcsec. Thus, this angular resolution allows us to measure the C17O emission by spatially resolving the inner and outer regions of the CO snow line. We also note that the angular resolution (0.4 arcsec) proposed here is consistent with those proposed for the line observations of C16O and C18O in the previous Cycle [ref 9, 10]. The same angular resolution can make it easier to construct a spatial distribution of the oxygen isotopic ratios when combined with the previous data. In summary, the requested lagest scale and angular resolution are the best choice to achieve our science goal.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our purpose is to explore any spatial variation of the oxygen isotope ratio by measuring the density distribution of C17O. Thus, we request the sensitivity high enough to detect the C17O emission in most regions of the disk. Based on the SMA results by Qi et al. (2011), the sensitivity of 1.5 mJy/beam (for the beam size of 0.4") is needed to detect (3 sig) the outer portion of the disk, at approximately 350 AU from the central star. The total observing time to achieve 1.5 mJy/beam is estimated with OT as 4.43 hours, with the velocity resolution of 0.86 km/s as described below.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
