    <prp:abstract>Oxygen, one of the most fundamental elements for the human beings, has three stable isotopes; 16O, 17O and 18O. The oxygen isotopic ratio varies among Solar System objects but the origin of such variation remains to be clarified. Thus, it is essential to identify the spatial distribution of oxygen isotopes in the pre-solar nebula for understanding what causes the variation of the oxygen isotopic ratios and how the Solar System including our Earth was formed. In this proposal, we plan to observe a protoplanetary disk around HD 163296 in order to make a high angular resolution (0.4 arcsec) map of the oxygen three-isotope ratio in the disk by detecting C17O (J=3-2) emission with ALMA. The unprecedented high sensitivity of ALMA will for the first time allow us to uncover the spatial distribution of weak C17O emission. Combined with the results of C16O and C18O observations proposed in the previous Cycle, the observations proposed here will provide the new and fundamental information on the radial distribution of C16O, C17O, and C18O in the disk, and also enable us to subsequently disclose the origin of variation of the oxygen isotopic ratio in the protoplanetary disk.</prp:abstract>
